---
import BaseLayout from '../../../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Subagents: Dedicated Helpers for Claude Code"
  description="Learn how to use /agents to create Subagents — dedicated helpers that Claude Code can delegate work to, keeping the main conversation's context clean."
  lang="en"
>
  <section class="section">
    <div class="container cc-subagents">
      <a class="back-link" href="/">&larr; Back to Home</a>

      <header class="detail-header">
        <h1 class="detail-title">Connect Claude Code to Tools, Teach It New Tricks, and Automate Repetitive Work</h1>
        <p class="detail-subtitle">
          We've already set up the basics for Claude Code — CLAUDE.md, memory management, context handling.
          The next stage isn't about stuffing more rules into the handbook. It's about giving Claude Code
          new abilities. Some let it see external tools, some let it follow fixed workflows, some let it
          farm out large tasks, and some automate repetitive actions. These abilities each have their own role.
        </p>
      </header>

      <!-- Section 1: What is a Subagent -->
      <h2 class="detail-heading">Subagents: Dedicated Helpers for Claude Code</h2>
      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        Think of a Subagent as a sidekick version of Claude Code. It's not just a block of instructions — it's a helper with
        its own context, its own tool permissions, and can even run on a specific model. When the main Claude Code hits a task
        that fits, it can delegate the work to the subagent, then pull back a summary when it's done.
      </p>
      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        The biggest advantage of this design is protecting the main conversation from getting flooded with details.
        For example, if you ask Claude Code to read many files, run a wide search, or sort through a pile of data,
        running all of that in the main conversation makes it heavy fast. A subagent handles the work on its own
        and only reports back a summary. This gives you the benefit of context isolation.
      </p>

      <div class="info-card">
        <p class="info-title">How to manage Subagents?</p>
        <p class="info-body">
          In Claude Code, the recommended way to create and manage Subagents is with the <code>/agents</code> command.<br />
          It opens an interactive interface where you can view available subagents, create new ones, edit tool access, delete custom subagents, or see which definitions are currently active.
        </p>
      </div>

      <!-- Section 2: Three ways to use -->
      <h2 class="detail-heading">Three Common Ways to Use a Subagent</h2>
      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        Say you want to create a new subagent, like <code>code-reviewer</code>. Once it's set up, you have three common ways to use it:
      </p>
      <ul class="usage-list">
        <li>
          <strong>Mention it in natural language</strong>: for example, "Please have code-reviewer look at my recent changes."
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Use @ to name it explicitly</strong>: this guarantees that specific helper will handle the task.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Set the whole session to a specific agent style</strong>: this is more advanced — we won't cover it here.
        </li>
      </ul>

      <!-- Main collapsible: Example steps -->
      <details class="collapsible">
        <summary class="collapsible-trigger">
          <span class="collapsible-icon"></span>
          <span class="collapsible-title">Example Steps for Using a Subagent</span>
        </summary>
        <div class="collapsible-body">

          <p class="detail-paragraph" style="margin-bottom: var(--space-2);">
            <strong>Creating code-reviewer</strong> (skip this section if you're using an existing subagent)
          </p>

          <ol class="step-list">
            <li class="step-item">
              <span class="step-num">1</span>
              <div class="step-body">
                <h3 class="step-title">Open the /agents interface</h3>
                <p class="step-desc">Open the Claude Code chat, type <code>/agents</code>, and select Agents.</p>
              </div>
            </li>

            <li class="step-item">
              <span class="step-num">2</span>
              <div class="step-body">
                <h3 class="step-title">Select Continue in Terminal</h3>
              </div>
            </li>

            <li class="step-item">
              <span class="step-num">3</span>
              <div class="step-body">
                <h3 class="step-title">Trust the folder and create a new agent</h3>
                <p class="step-desc">
                  Press Enter on "Yes, I trust this folder" and then on "Create new agent".
                </p>
              </div>
            </li>

            <li class="step-item">
              <span class="step-num">4</span>
              <div class="step-body">
                <h3 class="step-title">Choose the subagent's scope</h3>
                <p class="step-desc">
                  You'll see two options: "Project (.claude/agents/)" and "Personal (~/.claude/agents/)".
                  The former means this subagent is only available in this project; the latter means it's available across all projects.
                  For this demo, we'll pick "Project (.claude/agents/)".
                </p>
              </div>
            </li>

            <li class="step-item">
              <span class="step-num">5</span>
              <div class="step-body">
                <h3 class="step-title">Select Manual configuration</h3>
                <p class="step-desc">Press Enter on "Manual configuration".</p>
              </div>
            </li>
          </ol>

          <!-- Nested collapsible: Create a new subagent -->
          <details class="collapsible-nested">
            <summary class="collapsible-nested-trigger">
              <span class="collapsible-nested-icon"></span>
              <span class="collapsible-nested-title">6. Create a New Subagent</span>
            </summary>
            <div class="collapsible-nested-body">
              <p class="step-desc">Where: /agents interface</p>
              <p class="step-desc">
                Create a new subagent in the interface. For the name, enter: <code>code-reviewer</code>
              </p>

              <p class="step-desc" style="margin-top: var(--space-4);">
                Next, fill in the <strong>System prompt</strong> — this is the subagent's "internal working rules".
                It tells the helper "who you are, how you work, and what to focus on in your responses." For example:
              </p>
              <pre class="code-block"><code set:html={`You are a subagent dedicated to code review.

Your job is to inspect code, changes, or file contents the user provides, and find the most noteworthy issues, especially:

1. Possible bugs
2. Logic errors
3. Unhandled edge cases
4. Code that's hard to read or maintain
5. Duplicated logic
6. Obvious performance issues
7. Security risks

Follow these rules:
- Surface truly important issues first; don't put minor style nits at the top
- If you're unsure, say so — don't guess
- When explaining an issue, include "where it is", "why it's a problem", and "how to fix it"
- Keep responses well-organized; prefer bulleted lists
- If you don't see any obvious issues, say so explicitly
- Unless the user explicitly asks, do not modify the code — only review and suggest
- Explain things in plain language; avoid piling on jargon`} /></pre>

              <p class="step-desc" style="margin-top: var(--space-4);">
                Then fill in the <strong>Description</strong> — this tells the main Claude "when to delegate work to this helper." For example:
              </p>
              <pre class="code-block"><code set:html={`Dedicated to reviewing code changes — finding bugs, readability issues, edge cases, performance issues, and security risks.
Use when the user asks for a code review, wants recent changes checked, is hunting for bugs, or is evaluating code quality.`} /></pre>

              <div class="note-card">
                <p class="note-body">
                  Claude mainly uses the <strong>description</strong> to decide whether to delegate, while the subagent itself has its own custom system prompt.
                  If you want it to be invoked proactively more often, add phrasing like "use proactively" in the description.
                </p>
              </div>
            </div>
          </details>

          <!-- Nested collapsible: Configure tools -->
          <details class="collapsible-nested">
            <summary class="collapsible-nested-trigger">
              <span class="collapsible-nested-icon"></span>
              <span class="collapsible-nested-title">7. Configure Which Tools Your Subagent Can Use</span>
            </summary>
            <div class="collapsible-nested-body">
              <p class="step-desc">Where: /agents interface</p>

              <div class="tool-option">
                <h4 class="tool-option-title">All tools</h4>
                <p class="step-desc">
                  Give it every tool. If this option stays checked, the subagent inherits every tool currently available in the main conversation —
                  including built-in tools and MCP tools. This is the most convenient option and grants the broadest permissions.
                </p>
                <p class="step-desc"><strong>Good for:</strong> feature-complete helpers — ones that don't just read code but also edit files, run commands, and use external tools.</p>
              </div>

              <div class="tool-option">
                <h4 class="tool-option-title">Read-only tools</h4>
                <p class="step-desc">
                  Let it look, but not change anything. These tools are mainly for reading files, finding files, and searching content —
                  helping Claude Code understand the project without modifying it directly.
                </p>
                <p class="step-desc"><strong>Good for:</strong> code review, investigating issues, exploring project structure, research-before-reporting tasks.</p>
              </div>

              <div class="tool-option">
                <h4 class="tool-option-title">Edit tools</h4>
                <p class="step-desc">
                  Let it modify files. Claude Code has tools like Edit and Write that directly change files.
                  Turn on Edit tools and the subagent isn't just looking — it can actually make changes.
                </p>
                <p class="step-desc"><strong>Good for:</strong> bug-fix helpers, automated refactoring, applying suggested edits directly.</p>
              </div>

              <div class="tool-option">
                <h4 class="tool-option-title">Execution tools</h4>
                <p class="step-desc">
                  Let it run commands. Things like shell commands, starting services, running tests, and using git all fall in this category.
                </p>
                <p class="step-desc"><strong>Good for:</strong> test runners, build helpers, deployment checkers.</p>
              </div>

              <div class="tool-option">
                <h4 class="tool-option-title">MCP tools</h4>
                <p class="step-desc">
                  Let it use external tools you've connected. If your main conversation already has MCP servers attached,
                  the subagent inherits those MCP tools by default. You can also restrict it to only specific tools.
                </p>
                <p class="step-desc"><strong>Good for:</strong> helpers that need to look up external data, agents working alongside third-party tools.</p>
              </div>

              <div class="tool-option">
                <h4 class="tool-option-title">Other tools</h4>
                <p class="step-desc">
                  Auxiliary tools that don't fit the main categories — opening subagents, asking the user questions, managing tasks, switching to plan mode, working with worktrees, and so on.
                </p>
                <p class="step-desc"><strong>Good for:</strong> flow-control tasks.</p>
              </div>

              <div class="tool-option">
                <h4 class="tool-option-title">Show advanced options</h4>
                <p class="step-desc">
                  Opens finer-grained settings. This button usually lets you add further restrictions —
                  going beyond the broad categories to fine-tune individual tools. If this is your first time, you can skip it.
                </p>
              </div>

              <div class="note-card" style="margin-top: var(--space-4);">
                <p class="note-body">
                  The subagent we're building is <code>code-reviewer</code>, which is a review-type helper. It needs to look, search, and analyze —
                  but shouldn't directly modify files. So the recommendation is: uncheck All tools, leave only <strong>Read-only tools</strong>, then press Continue.
                </p>
              </div>
            </div>
          </details>

          <ol class="step-list" start="8">
            <li class="step-item">
              <span class="step-num">8</span>
              <div class="step-body">
                <h3 class="step-title">Select model</h3>
                <p class="step-desc">
                  Where: /agents interface<br />
                  Sonnet is a solid default — it balances capability and speed well for analyzing code patterns. But pick based on your own needs.
                </p>
              </div>
            </li>

            <li class="step-item">
              <span class="step-num">9</span>
              <div class="step-body">
                <h3 class="step-title">Choose a color</h3>
                <p class="step-desc">
                  Where: /agents interface<br />
                  Pick whatever color you like. It's just a visual cue so you can tell which subagent is running in the interface.
                </p>
              </div>
            </li>
          </ol>

          <!-- Nested collapsible: Configure memory -->
          <details class="collapsible-nested">
            <summary class="collapsible-nested-trigger">
              <span class="collapsible-nested-icon"></span>
              <span class="collapsible-nested-title">10. Configure Memory</span>
            </summary>
            <div class="collapsible-nested-body">
              <p class="step-desc">Where: /agents interface</p>
              <p class="step-desc">
                Decide whether this subagent should have its own long-term memory, and where that memory should live.
                If memory is on, the helper isn't just "one-and-done" — it gradually builds up notes on the rules it's observed,
                common issues, code style, and project habits, so it can reuse them later.
              </p>

              <div class="memory-option">
                <h4 class="memory-option-title">Project scope (.claude/agent-memory/) (Recommended)</h4>
                <p class="step-desc">
                  Stores the subagent's memory inside the current project. Good for cases where "this memory is only useful for this project."
                  Things like the project's naming conventions, folder structure, common trouble spots, and code style —
                  all a good fit for project scope.
                </p>
                <p class="step-desc step-desc--hint">
                  Think of it as: this helper gradually learns "how we do things in this project."
                </p>
              </div>

              <div class="memory-option">
                <h4 class="memory-option-title">None (no persistent memory)</h4>
                <p class="step-desc">
                  No long-term memory at all. The subagent is one-and-done every time — nothing it learns carries over.
                </p>
                <p class="step-desc step-desc--hint">
                  Think of it as: this helper has short-term memory, but no long-term notebook.
                </p>
              </div>

              <div class="memory-option">
                <h4 class="memory-option-title">User scope (~/.claude/agent-memory/)</h4>
                <p class="step-desc">
                  Stores memory in your personal Claude config folder, so it's available across all projects.
                  Good if what the subagent learns is "not just for one project" — your personal coding style, the review standards you use,
                  the debugging instincts you rely on. Those can live here.
                </p>
                <p class="step-desc step-desc--hint">
                  Think of it as: this helper learns "how you work," not just one project's habits.
                </p>
              </div>

              <div class="memory-option">
                <h4 class="memory-option-title">Local scope (.claude/agent-memory-local/)</h4>
                <p class="step-desc">
                  Memory stays in the current project and isn't meant to be shared. Similar to project scope,
                  but project scope is "versioned and shareable with the team," while local scope is
                  "private notes on my machine that I don't want in the repo."
                </p>
                <p class="step-desc step-desc--hint">
                  Think of it as: this helper remembers project-specific things, but the notes are personal — not something you'd hand to the team.
                </p>
              </div>

              <div class="note-card" style="margin-top: var(--space-4);">
                <p class="note-body">
                  Since we're just testing for now, choose <strong>None</strong>.
                </p>
              </div>
            </div>
          </details>

          <ol class="step-list" start="11">
            <li class="step-item">
              <span class="step-num">11</span>
              <div class="step-body">
                <h3 class="step-title">Save</h3>
                <p class="step-desc">
                  Where: /agents interface<br />
                  You'll land on a summary screen. Press <kbd>s</kbd> or <kbd>Enter</kbd> to save;
                  press <kbd>e</kbd> to save and then open the file for editing. Once saved, the subagent is ready to use immediately.
                </p>
              </div>
            </li>
          </ol>

          <!-- Usage section -->
          <h3 class="subsection-title">How to Use code-reviewer After Creation</h3>

          <div class="usage-card">
            <h4 class="usage-card-title">1. Mention It in Natural Language</h4>
            <p class="step-desc">
              (No guarantee it'll actually delegate — Claude Code may decide it can handle the task itself.)
            </p>
            <p class="step-desc">Type something like this into the Claude Code chat:</p>
            <pre class="code-block code-block--command"><code>Please have code-reviewer look at my recent code changes.</code></pre>
            <p class="step-desc">
              Claude Code uses the subagent's description to decide whether to delegate — automatic delegation mostly depends on how you wrote the description.
            </p>
          </div>

          <div class="usage-card">
            <h4 class="usage-card-title">2. Use @ to Name It Explicitly</h4>
            <p class="step-desc">
              In the Claude Code chat, type <code>@</code>, pick your subagent from the dropdown, and then fill in the task. For example:
            </p>
            <pre class="code-block code-block--command"><code>@"code-reviewer (agent)" check my recent changes and list the most important issues to fix first.</code></pre>
          </div>

          <div class="note-card" style="margin-top: var(--space-4);">
            <p class="note-body">
              <strong>Key takeaway:</strong> if the task involves reading a lot, running many searches, but you only want a summary at the end —
              it's a perfect fit for a Subagent.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </details>

      <!-- Summary -->
      <div class="summary-card">
        <p class="summary-title">Key Takeaways</p>
        <ul class="summary-list">
          <li><strong>Subagent</strong>: a sidekick version of Claude Code with its own context, tool permissions, and model settings.</li>
          <li><strong>Context isolation</strong>: the subagent handles work on its own and only reports back a summary, keeping the main conversation clean.</li>
          <li><strong>/agents</strong>: the interactive interface for creating and managing subagents.</li>
          <li><strong>Tool permissions</strong>: fine-tune which tools each subagent can use — read-only, editing, execution, and so on.</li>
          <li><strong>Memory settings</strong>: choose Project, User, Local scope, or no memory at all.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>

<style>
  .cc-subagents {
    max-width: 52rem;
  }

  .back-link {
    display: inline-block;
    margin-bottom: var(--space-8);
    font-size: var(--text-sm);
    color: var(--color-accent);
    text-decoration: none;
  }

  .back-link:hover {
    text-decoration: underline;
  }

  /* Header */
  .detail-header {
    margin-bottom: var(--space-12);
    padding-bottom: var(--space-6);
    border-bottom: 1px solid var(--color-border);
  }

  .detail-title {
    font-size: var(--text-3xl);
    font-weight: 700;
    color: var(--color-heading);
    margin-bottom: var(--space-3);
    line-height: 1.3;
  }

  .detail-subtitle {
    font-size: var(--text-base);
    color: var(--color-text-secondary);
    line-height: 1.8;
  }

  /* Section headings */
  .detail-heading {
    font-size: var(--text-xl);
    font-weight: 600;
    color: var(--color-heading);
    margin-top: var(--space-12);
    margin-bottom: var(--space-4);
    padding-bottom: var(--space-2);
    border-bottom: 1px solid var(--color-border);
  }

  .detail-paragraph {
    font-size: var(--text-base);
    color: var(--color-text);
    line-height: 1.9;
    margin-bottom: var(--space-4);
  }

  .detail-paragraph strong {
    color: var(--color-heading);
    font-weight: 600;
  }

  /* ── Usage list ── */
  .usage-list {
    list-style: none;
    padding: 0;
    margin: var(--space-4) 0 var(--space-6);
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    gap: var(--space-3);
    font-size: var(--text-base);
    color: var(--color-text);
    line-height: 1.9;
  }

  .usage-list li {
    padding-left: var(--space-6);
    position: relative;
  }

  .usage-list li::before {
    content: '\2713';
    position: absolute;
    left: 0;
    color: var(--color-accent);
    font-weight: 700;
  }

  .usage-list strong {
    color: var(--color-heading);
    font-weight: 600;
  }

  /* ── Collapsible sections (purple, top-level) ── */
  .collapsible {
    margin-top: var(--space-6);
    border: 1px solid var(--color-border);
    border-left: 4px solid #8b5cf6;
    border-radius: var(--border-radius);
    overflow: hidden;
    transition: border-color var(--transition);
  }

  .collapsible[open] {
    border-top-color: #8b5cf6;
    border-right-color: #8b5cf6;
    border-bottom-color: #8b5cf6;
  }

  .collapsible-trigger {
    display: flex;
    align-items: center;
    gap: var(--space-3);
    width: 100%;
    padding: var(--space-4) var(--space-6);
    background-color: var(--color-bg-secondary);
    cursor: pointer;
    list-style: none;
    user-select: none;
    transition: background-color var(--transition);
  }

  .collapsible-trigger::-webkit-details-marker {
    display: none;
  }

  .collapsible-trigger:hover {
    background-color: var(--color-tag-bg);
  }

  .collapsible-icon {
    flex-shrink: 0;
    width: 1.25rem;
    height: 1.25rem;
    position: relative;
    transition: transform 0.2s ease;
  }

  .collapsible-icon::before,
  .collapsible-icon::after {
    content: '';
    position: absolute;
    background-color: #8b5cf6;
    border-radius: 1px;
  }

  .collapsible-icon::before {
    top: 50%;
    left: 0;
    width: 100%;
    height: 2px;
    transform: translateY(-50%);
  }

  .collapsible-icon::after {
    top: 0;
    left: 50%;
    width: 2px;
    height: 100%;
    transform: translateX(-50%);
    transition: opacity 0.2s ease;
  }

  .collapsible[open] .collapsible-icon::after {
    opacity: 0;
  }

  .collapsible-title {
    font-size: var(--text-lg);
    font-weight: 700;
    color: var(--color-heading);
  }

  .collapsible-body {
    padding: var(--space-6);
  }

  /* ── Nested collapsible (orange) ── */
  .collapsible-nested {
    margin: var(--space-4) 0;
    border: 1px solid var(--color-border);
    border-left: 4px solid #f97316;
    border-radius: var(--border-radius);
    overflow: hidden;
    transition: border-color var(--transition);
  }

  .collapsible-nested[open] {
    border-top-color: #f97316;
    border-right-color: #f97316;
    border-bottom-color: #f97316;
  }

  .collapsible-nested-trigger {
    display: flex;
    align-items: center;
    gap: var(--space-3);
    width: 100%;
    padding: var(--space-4) var(--space-6);
    background-color: var(--color-bg-secondary);
    cursor: pointer;
    list-style: none;
    user-select: none;
    transition: background-color var(--transition);
  }

  .collapsible-nested-trigger::-webkit-details-marker {
    display: none;
  }

  .collapsible-nested-trigger:hover {
    background-color: #fff7ed;
  }

  :root[data-theme='dark'] .collapsible-nested-trigger:hover {
    background-color: rgba(249, 115, 22, 0.08);
  }

  .collapsible-nested-icon {
    flex-shrink: 0;
    width: 1.25rem;
    height: 1.25rem;
    position: relative;
    transition: transform 0.2s ease;
  }

  .collapsible-nested-icon::before,
  .collapsible-nested-icon::after {
    content: '';
    position: absolute;
    background-color: #f97316;
    border-radius: 1px;
  }

  .collapsible-nested-icon::before {
    top: 50%;
    left: 0;
    width: 100%;
    height: 2px;
    transform: translateY(-50%);
  }

  .collapsible-nested-icon::after {
    top: 0;
    left: 50%;
    width: 2px;
    height: 100%;
    transform: translateX(-50%);
    transition: opacity 0.2s ease;
  }

  .collapsible-nested[open] .collapsible-nested-icon::after {
    opacity: 0;
  }

  .collapsible-nested-title {
    font-size: var(--text-base);
    font-weight: 700;
    color: var(--color-heading);
  }

  .collapsible-nested-body {
    padding: var(--space-6);
  }

  /* ── Info card ── */
  .info-card {
    margin: var(--space-4) 0 var(--space-6);
    padding: var(--space-6);
    border-left: 4px solid var(--color-accent);
    background-color: var(--color-bg-secondary);
    border-radius: var(--border-radius);
  }

  .info-title {
    font-size: var(--text-xs);
    font-weight: 700;
    color: var(--color-accent);
    letter-spacing: 0.08em;
    margin-bottom: var(--space-2);
    text-transform: uppercase;
  }

  .info-body {
    font-size: var(--text-base);
    color: var(--color-heading);
    font-weight: 500;
    line-height: 1.8;
    margin: 0;
  }

  /* ── Tool & Memory option cards ── */
